The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Hindujas buy European bank
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Hindujas buy European bank
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Calcutta, May 21: The Hinduja group has acquired the private banking arm of Belgium-based KBC  KBL European Private Bankers  for 1.35 billion euros (Rs 8,770 crore or $1.69 billion).        
	KBL European Private Bankers was put up for sale by KBC as part of a restructuring plan by the European Commission in return for 7 billion euros of state aid. The divestment is considered as the largest so far by KBC.         
	KBC, which received the aid of 7 billion euros last November, has pledged to wind down some businesses and trim its balance sheet.        
	As well as providing a stable home, continuity and careful stewardship for KBL, the (Hinduja) group will also give the bank greater access to the fast-growing West Asian, Indian and Asian markets, KBC said in a statement.         
	The Hinduja group has interests in banking, oil and automotives.         
	They also have a private banking arm called Hinduja Bank Switzerland, which has operations in Europe, West Asia and India.         
	The Hindujas also have a retail presence through IndusInd Bank in India. IndusInd bank has two million customers and a balance sheet of $8 billion.         
	The acquisition of KBL, one of Europes largest onshore private banking units with 47 billion euros of assets under management and 37 billion euros in assets under custody, will strengthen the Hinduja foothold in the European market.        
	KBC is present in 55 locations across Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, Monaco, the Netherlands, Poland, Spain, Switzerland and the UK. KBC also has an asset management JV with the Union Bank in India.         
	We plan to invest in the business, maintaining each of the subsidiaries, while also providing KBL with access to the fast growing markets of West Asia, the Indian subcontinent and Asia, Hinduja Group chairman Srichand P. Hinduja said in a joint statement.                                                                                                                                       
